<node TEXT="poker psychology" FOLDED="true" POSITION="right" ID="ID_1448037935" CREATED="1716512129264" MODIFIED="1716512135772">
<edge COLOR="#ff0000"/>
<node TEXT="Understanding and Accepting the Realities of Poker&#xa;Playing for the Long Term&#xa;Emphasizing Correct Decisions over Making Money&#xa;Desensitizing Yourself to Money&#xa;Leaving Your Ego at the Door&#xa;Removing All Emotion from Decisions&#xa;Dedication to a Continuous Cycle of Analysis and Improvement&#xa;Recognizing the importance of the Poker Mindset&#xa;Coping with losing big pots, downswings, and tilt&#xa;Proper bankroll management&#xa;Studying opponents and advanced topics" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_548088443" CREATED="1716512135781" MODIFIED="1716512221230">
<node TEXT="    Understanding and Accepting the Realities of Poker: Acknowledging the inherent uncertainties, risks, and fluctuations in poker is vital for developing a realistic perspective on the game.&#xa;&#xa;    Playing for the Long Term: Focusing on long-term results rather than short-term outcomes helps players maintain consistency and make decisions that benefit their overall performance.&#xa;&#xa;    Emphasizing Correct Decisions over Making Money: Prioritizing making sound and strategic decisions over solely chasing profits leads to more sustainable success in poker.&#xa;&#xa;    Desensitizing Yourself to Money: Detaching emotions from the monetary aspect of the game can help players make rational choices and avoid being swayed by financial considerations.&#xa;&#xa;    Leaving Your Ego at the Door: Putting aside personal pride and ego allows players to approach the game objectively and make decisions based on logic rather than emotions.&#xa;&#xa;    Removing All Emotion from Decisions: Striving to make decisions based on logic and strategy rather than being influenced by emotional reactions leads to more effective gameplay.&#xa;&#xa;    Dedication to a Continuous Cycle of Analysis and Improvement: Committing to ongoing self-assessment, learning, and skill enhancement is essential for evolving as a poker player and staying competitive.&#xa;&#xa;    Recognizing the Importance of the Poker Mindset: Understanding the significance of mindset, mental resilience, and psychological fortitude in poker is crucial for navigating challenges and maximizing performance.&#xa;&#xa;    Coping with Losing Big Pots, Downswings, and Tilt: Developing strategies to manage setbacks, losses, and emotional challenges in poker is key to maintaining composure and focus during difficult moments.&#xa;&#xa;    Proper Bankroll Management: Effectively managing one&apos;s bankroll to withstand variance, protect funds, and sustain long-term play is a cornerstone of successful poker strategy.&#xa;&#xa;    Studying Opponents and Advanced Topics: Engaging in in-depth analysis of opponents, advanced strategies, and game dynamics enhances a player&apos;s understanding and competitive edge in poker." ID="ID_1993246646" CREATED="1716512472761" MODIFIED="1716512478000"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Tilt in poker signifies a condition of emotional or mental distress that causes a player to make subpar decisions or perform below their usual level of skill. When a player experiences tilt, their emotions can obscure their reasoning, resulting in unwise actions and the possibility of substantial losses. Tilt can appear in different guises, including overly aggressive, overly passive, overly tight play, or engaging in overly intricate and misleading strategies. It is crucial for poker players to identify when they are on tilt and implement measures to reestablish command over their emotions and strategic thinking to prevent negative repercussions on their gameplay." ID="ID_1147479387" CREATED="1716512343162" MODIFIED="1716512346692"/>
<node TEXT="some strategies to help you cope with losing big pots effectively:&#xa;&#xa;    Maintain Emotional Control: It&apos;s essential to stay composed and avoid letting emotions like frustration, anger, or disappointment cloud your judgment. Take a deep breath, stay focused, and avoid making impulsive decisions based on emotions&#xa;&#xa;,&#xa;&#xa;.&#xa;&#xa;Analyze the Hand Objectively: Instead of dwelling on the outcome of the hand, focus on analyzing the decisions you made leading up to the big pot loss. Evaluate whether your actions were sound based on the information available at the time, rather than solely focusing on the result&#xa;,&#xa;&#xa;.&#xa;&#xa;Learn from the Experience: Losing big pots can provide valuable learning opportunities. Use these moments to reflect on your strategy, identify potential mistakes or weaknesses in your game, and make adjustments to improve your future decision-making&#xa;,&#xa;&#xa;.&#xa;&#xa;Maintain Perspective: Remember that variance is an inherent part of poker, and losing big pots is a natural occurrence in the game. Keep a long-term view of your poker journey and focus on making consistent, profitable decisions over time rather than getting fixated on individual outcomes&#xa;,&#xa;&#xa;.&#xa;&#xa;Seek Support: Discussing your experiences with fellow poker players, coaches, or mentors can provide valuable insights and emotional support. Sharing your thoughts and feelings with others who understand the challenges of poker can help you process and move on from big losses&#xa;, ." ID="ID_284641998" CREATED="1716512393098" MODIFIED="1716512395695"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="equity realization" FOLDED="true" POSITION="left" ID="ID_821417311" CREATED="1716512673464" MODIFIED="1716512679537">
<edge COLOR="#0000ff"/>
<node TEXT="Equity Realization involves understanding how much of your hand&apos;s equity you can actually realize in a given situation, which is crucial for making profitable decisions." ID="ID_272843985" CREATED="1716512679540" MODIFIED="1716512685682"/>
<node TEXT="even if a hand has significant raw equity, it may not be profitable to play if the Equity Realization factor is low." ID="ID_510626097" CREATED="1716512706503" MODIFIED="1716512709985"/>
<node TEXT="converting equity into profit depends on various factors such as betting decisions, opponent actions, and board texture" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1906395942" CREATED="1716512782191" MODIFIED="1716512800473">
<node TEXT="The texture of the board can be categorized based on factors such as:&#xa;&#xa;    Wet Boards: Boards with coordinated and connected cards that offer numerous straight and flush possibilities. Wet boards tend to favor drawing hands and can lead to more aggressive and dynamic gameplay.&#xa;&#xa;    Dry Boards: Boards with uncoordinated and disconnected cards that limit the number of possible strong hands. Dry boards are less likely to produce big draws and typically result in more straightforward and less aggressive play.&#xa;&#xa;    Coordinated Boards: Boards where the community cards are closely related and offer multiple straight and flush possibilities. Coordinated boards can create complex post-flop scenarios and require careful consideration of hand strength and potential combinations.&#xa;&#xa;    Monotone Boards: Boards where all the community cards are of the same suit, increasing the likelihood of flush draws. Monotone boards can lead to intense action and strategic decisions based on the potential for flush combinations." ID="ID_664710344" CREATED="1716512835391" MODIFIED="1716512837828"/>
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="poker concepts" FOLDED="true" POSITION="right" ID="ID_1393899656" CREATED="1716518617968" MODIFIED="1716518628786">
<edge COLOR="#00ff00"/>
<node TEXT="pot odds" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1595912817" CREATED="1716518628797" MODIFIED="1716518631944">
<node TEXT="Here&apos;s how pot odds work:&#xa;&#xa;    Calculating Pot Odds: Pot odds are calculated by dividing the size of the pot by the cost of the call. For example, if there is 100 in the pot and the bet to call is 20, the pot odds are 100:20 or 5:1.&#xa;&#xa;    Decision Making: Once you know the pot odds, you compare them to your chances of winning the hand. If your chances of winning are better than the pot odds, it is generally a profitable call. If your chances are worse, folding may be the better decision.&#xa;&#xa;    Example: If the pot contains 100 and your opponent bets 20, you need to call 20 to potentially win 120 (100+20). If you believe you have a better than 1 in 6 (5:1) chance of winning the hand, based on your hand strength and the cards on the board, then calling would be a mathematically sound decision." ID="ID_1393239071" CREATED="1716518631955" MODIFIED="1716518748994"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="position" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_573034927" CREATED="1716518911157" MODIFIED="1716518913686">
<node TEXT="Position: Your position relative to the dealer button is crucial. Being in late position gives you an advantage because you have more information about your opponents&apos; actions before you have to make a decision. Example: You&apos;re on the button (the dealer position) and everyone has folded to you. You can raise with a wider range of hands because you have seen how many players are likely to fold before it&apos;s your turn to act." ID="ID_599898171" CREATED="1716518913693" MODIFIED="1716518918311"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="bluffing and semi-bluffing" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1545546087" CREATED="1716518964774" MODIFIED="1716518972894">
<node TEXT="Bluffing and Semi-Bluffing: Knowing when to bluff or semi-bluff (bluffing with a hand that has potential to improve) is key. It involves understanding your opponent&apos;s tendencies and the board texture. Example: You raise pre-flop with a suited connector like 8-9 of hearts, the flop comes A-K-Q with two hearts. You don&apos;t have a made hand, but you have a flush draw and a straight draw. Betting here is a semi-bluff because even if your opponent calls, you still have a chance to win the hand by hitting your draw on the turn or river." ID="ID_1082595964" CREATED="1716518972904" MODIFIED="1716518983738"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="reading opponents" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_817781477" CREATED="1716519013517" MODIFIED="1716519017046">
<node TEXT="Reading Opponents: Paying attention to your opponents&apos; betting patterns, tendencies, and body language can give you valuable information about the strength of their hand. Example: You notice that whenever a player makes a big bet, they tend to have a strong hand, but when they hesitate before betting, they often have a weak hand or are considering a bluff." ID="ID_1201511418" CREATED="1716519017049" MODIFIED="1716519019552"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="bankroll management" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1703769566" CREATED="1716519042877" MODIFIED="1716519047398">
<node TEXT="Bankroll Management: Managing your bankroll effectively is crucial for long-term success in poker. This involves only risking a small portion of your bankroll on any single game or tournament to avoid going broke during downswings. Example: If you have a bankroll of $1,000, it&apos;s generally recommended to not risk more than 5% ($50) on any single cash game or tournament buy-in." ID="ID_1700883089" CREATED="1716519047401" MODIFIED="1716519050800"/>
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="poker terms" FOLDED="true" POSITION="left" ID="ID_1986069352" CREATED="1716519508546" MODIFIED="1716519513745">
<edge COLOR="#ff00ff"/>
<node TEXT="Double Belly Buster Straight Draw: A non-consecutive four-card straight draw where two inside cards can complete a straight. Example: Holding 7&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 8&#x2666;&#xfe0f; on a board of 4&#x2663;&#xfe0f; 5&#x2666;&#xfe0f; 9&#x2665;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Nut Flush: The highest possible flush available in a given situation. Example: Holding A&#x2660;&#xfe0f; K&#x2660;&#xfe0f; on a board of 10&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 7&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 3&#x2660;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Wraparound Straight Draw: A straight draw where cards from both ends of the sequence can complete a straight. Example: Holding 7&#x2666;&#xfe0f; 8&#x2666;&#xfe0f; on a board of 5&#x2663;&#xfe0f; 6&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 9&#x2663;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Backdoor Flush/ Straight: Drawing to a flush or straight using both the turn and river cards. Example: Holding 8&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 9&#x2660;&#xfe0f; on a flop of 2&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 5&#x2666;&#xfe0f; K&#x2663;&#xfe0f;, then seeing the turn and river come 4&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 6&#x2660;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Gutshot Straight Draw: A four-card straight draw where only one rank of card can complete the straight. Example: Holding 7&#x2666;&#xfe0f; 9&#x2666;&#xfe0f; on a board of 5&#x2663;&#xfe0f; 6&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 8&#x2663;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Double Gutshot Straight Draw: A straight draw where two ranks of cards can complete the straight. Example: Holding 7&#x2666;&#xfe0f; 9&#x2666;&#xfe0f; on a board of 5&#x2663;&#xfe0f; 6&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 8&#x2663;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Overpair: A pocket pair higher than any of the community cards. Example: Holding Q&#x2660;&#xfe0f; Q&#x2663;&#xfe0f; on a board of 3&#x2666;&#xfe0f; 6&#x2660;&#xfe0f; 9&#x2665;&#xfe0f;.&#xa;&#xa;Float: Calling a bet on one street with the intention of taking the pot away on a later street, often as a bluff. Example: Calling a continuation bet on the flop with a weak hand intending to bluff on the turn or river.&#xa;&#xa;Squeeze Play: A preflop or postflop play where a player re-raises after there has been a raise and a call in front of them, with the intention of forcing both opponents to fold. Example: Player A raises, Player B calls, and Player C (with a strong hand or as a bluff) re-raises to pressure both opponents.&#xa;&#xa;Reverse Implied Odds: The potential loss in a hand exceeds the potential gain. Example: Holding a medium pocket pair in a multiway pot against aggressive opponents who may have higher pocket pairs.&#xa;&#xa;Polarized Range: A range of hands that consists mainly of very strong hands or bluffs, with few medium-strength hands. Example: A player only bets big with either strong made hands or missed draws, never with medium-strength hands." ID="ID_1364459339" CREATED="1716519514739" MODIFIED="1716519525385"/>
<node TEXT="    Range Advantage: When a player&apos;s range of possible hands is stronger than their opponent&apos;s range based on the betting action and community cards. Example: A preflop raiser on a tight table likely has a range advantage over the caller.&#xa;&#xa;    Merge: To play hands in a manner that blurs the distinction between strong and weak hands, making it difficult for opponents to accurately read your holdings. Example: Mixing in bluffs with strong hands in your betting patterns to keep opponents guessing.&#xa;&#xa;    Thin Value Bet: A small bet made with a moderately strong hand, aiming to extract value from weaker hands while avoiding a raise from stronger hands. Example: Betting with top pair on the river on a dry board against a passive opponent.&#xa;&#xa;    Blocker: A card in your hand that reduces the likelihood of your opponent having a specific hand, either by blocking potential combinations or reducing the probability of certain holdings. Example: Holding the ace of spades when there are three spades on the board, reducing the likelihood of your opponent having a flush.&#xa;&#xa;    Range Merging: Combining strong hands and bluffs into one&apos;s betting range in a way that makes it difficult for opponents to categorize your hand accurately. Example: Betting with both top pair and a draw on the turn to disguise the strength of your hand.&#xa;&#xa;    Leveling: Engaging in a mental battle with opponents where each player tries to outthink the other by anticipating the other&apos;s thought process and adjusting their own strategy accordingly. Example: Making a large river bet with a marginal hand, expecting your opponent to overthink and fold a stronger hand.&#xa;&#xa;    Exploitative Play: Adjusting one&apos;s strategy based on specific tendencies or weaknesses observed in opponents, rather than adhering strictly to theoretical principles. Example: Continuously bluffing against a player who frequently folds to aggression.&#xa;&#xa;    Reverse Tell: Deliberately displaying behavior or making plays that contradict one&apos;s actual hand strength, in an attempt to mislead opponents. Example: Acting confidently and making exaggerated movements when bluffing to give the impression of strength.&#xa;&#xa;    Pot Odds: The ratio of the current size of the pot to the size of the bet required to call, used to determine whether calling a bet is profitable based on the likelihood of improving one&apos;s hand. Example: If the pot is $100 and the opponent bets $20, the pot odds are 100:20, or 5:1.&#xa;&#xa;    Fold Equity: The additional equity gained by betting or raising as a bluff, causing opponents to fold hands that would have won at showdown. Example: Shoving all-in with a draw on the turn to make opponents fold stronger made hands.&#xa;&#xa;    Spr: Stack-to-Pot Ratio, a measure of how many times the size of the pot a player has compared to their remaining stack. Example: If the pot is $100 and a player has $400 behind, the SPR is 4.&#xa;&#xa;    Range Construction: The process of assigning possible hands to opponents based on their actions throughout a hand, used to make informed decisions about betting, calling, or folding. Example: Narrowing an opponent&apos;s range based on their preflop raising range and postflop betting patterns." ID="ID_1006903161" CREATED="1716519645514" MODIFIED="1716519651324"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="betting" FOLDED="true" POSITION="right" ID="ID_1986072218" CREATED="1716519974752" MODIFIED="1716519977353">
<edge COLOR="#00ffff"/>
<node TEXT="elementary" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1490840896" CREATED="1716519977365" MODIFIED="1716519985889">
<node TEXT="    Hand Strength: Bet more with stronger hands and less with weaker hands. For example, you might bet aggressively with pocket aces but only call with a low pair like 22.&#xa;&#xa;    Position: Bet more when you&apos;re in a later position, as you have more information about your opponents&apos; actions. For example, if you&apos;re on the button and everyone has checked to you, you might bet to try to steal the pot.&#xa;&#xa;    Opponent Tendencies: Adjust your bet sizing based on your opponents&apos; tendencies. Against tight players, you might bet smaller to extract value, while against loose players, you might bet larger to protect your hand.&#xa;&#xa;    Pot Size: Bet relative to the size of the pot. For example, you might bet half the pot for a value bet or a pot-sized bet for a bluff.&#xa;&#xa;    Board Texture: Consider the texture of the community cards when deciding how much to bet. Bet more on dry boards (with fewer draws) and less on wet boards (with many possible draws).&#xa;&#xa;    Stack Sizes: Adjust your bet sizing based on yours and your opponents&apos; stack sizes. You might bet smaller if you or your opponent have a short stack, as this commits fewer chips to the pot.&#xa;&#xa;    Image at the Table: Adjust your bet sizing based on your table image. If you&apos;ve been playing tight, you might bet larger when you do enter a pot to capitalize on your perceived strength.&#xa;&#xa;    Blind Levels in Tournaments: Adjust your bet sizing based on the blind levels in tournaments. As blinds increase, you might need to bet larger to maintain pressure on your opponents.&#xa;&#xa;    Previous Action: Consider the previous action in the hand when deciding how much to bet. For example, if you&apos;ve been raising pre-flop and continuation betting on the flop, you might need to size your turn bet larger to maintain credibility.&#xa;&#xa;    Potential Hands of Opponents: Bet more when you think your opponents have weaker hands and less when you think they have stronger hands. For example, if the flop comes with three low cards and your opponent has been playing aggressively, you might bet big to represent a strong hand.&#xa;&#xa;    Table Dynamics: Consider the overall dynamics at the table when deciding how much to bet. If the table is playing passively, you might bet larger to capitalize on this and build the pot.&#xa;&#xa;    Your Overall Strategy: Finally, consider your overall strategy and adjust your bet sizing accordingly. If you&apos;re playing a more aggressive style, you might bet larger more frequently to apply pressure to your opponents." ID="ID_1791095786" CREATED="1716519985892" MODIFIED="1716519990395"/>
</node>
</node>
</node>
